I'd like to start by stating that I had 5 Siberian Huskies and the first time I had an experience at this facility was on December 27, 2017 when I had an emergency with my male Husky, Shadow.  I had taken him to the Torrance Emergency Clinic on Torrance Blvd only to find that they had moved. By the time I found where they were, Shadow passed away in my car. So, I am very sensitive about when there is an emergency with my pets and making sure I know where I am going for help. Since then, I have had many visits at ACCESS Torrance with my other four Huskies and the services rendered by the doctors have been great! I have never had a problem until today, June 22, 2020 at around 1:30 a.m.

My female Husky, Nikki, needed emergency help. She had just been to ACCESS Torrance two weeks earlier one day prior to having surgery to remove three tumors, which ended up being cancerous. One week later, she wasn't doing good and she had to have a drain removed from her stomach. Her primary Vet thought the worst and suggested I put her to sleep. I decided not to rush into such a drastic decision, which I am glad I did because she is actually doing much better. However, there was a problem with fluids building up and the doctor had to drain the fluids. This morning, when I took her to ACCESS, I thought that the fluids had built up again and she seemed to be in pain so I drove her over to ACCESS. All I could think about was that I wouldn't make it to another hospital and she would die on me too!

The receptionist at ACCESS need more training on how to interact with pet owners in the event of an emergency! <GmapID>0x80dd4ac99116444b:0x8d2bc86ebcfe0a0f<//GmapID>< text>
TLDR: Doctor Melissa Roth and Katrina and all the nurses at ACCESS saved my dog's life, bringing her back from a 105 multiday fever, not eating or drinking, shaking when I tried to touch her, urinating on herself, and an incredible fast spreading skin infection combo. Cannot recommend them enough. Save their address and number in your phone and take your animal to them. The tools and staff they have to help heal your loved one are amazing. Because of COVID they have you park and wait in your car and a nurse will come and bring your animal inside the hospital, and call you with any updates, just FYI while COVID is still applicable.

Full Story:

My 8 year old german shepherd had a 105 fever and was lethargic, not eating or drinking, her normal vet is VCA Hermosa and it was after hours, and they recommended we go to ACCESS Animal Hospital. I'd never taken my dog to an animal hospital before so I wasn't sure what to expect.

I called ACCESS and they were so nice on the phone. Talking to them made me feel at ease. I took my dog in at midnight on Sunday and they checked her out, gave her fluids under the skin and took an xray of her lungs and abdomen to see if they could find anything. Thankfully her x-rays were clean. They gave her an anti-nausea shot to see if she would eat and drink after it. We originally thought she just ate some bad food and was having an elevated temperature as it work through her system

We took her home and then checked her out again in the morning. She still had the fever, but she was at least drinking, unlike the night before. So thinking it was no longer fever due to food, and that it wasn't going away by itself,

We decided to take her back to ACCESS and we met the wonderful Dr. Roth. She really took care of my dog, and was in constant contact with us about her recommendations and care opinions for my girl.

My dog's fever case was a bit out of the normal, the basic tests for infection kept coming back as normal, yet she still had a 105 fever, and then she got a rapidly spreading skin infection. It was weird, so we opted for more tests.

With the help of Dr. Roth we ended up doing a blood test, a urine test, a tick test, a blood clotting test and finally an ultrasound to check for an infection, a UTI, tick diseases, arthritic joint infection and any infections localized in her smaller organs.

These tests were not all at once, we did one at a time to see if we could find anything, we only did the next test after the results came back negative. They were not pushy about tests at all. After every test, Dr. Roth would call us and explain the pros and cons of doing each and every test, and she gave us her opinion on whether or not she would do each test for her own sick pet if she was in our situation. She also called us after every result came in. We ended up talking to her a lot.

Dr. Roth and her medical assistant Katrina were incredibly warm, comforting, knowledgeable and empathetic. Dr. Roth educated us on all of our opitions and all of the tests we could do at ACCESS to try and figure out what was wrong with our girl. Katrina was my email point of contact relaying what Dr. Roth said about my dog when they looked at pictures I sent her during her recovery.

We eventually left with an antibiotic for the fever, an antibiotic for her skin infection, and an anti-tick medication. My puppy got immediately better and had been better ever since going to ACCESS. I had been in email communication with Katrina and Dr. Roth to monitor her recovery and they were so responsive and so excited that Jordan was getting better.

It was so comforting knowing that they cared so much about my dog. They helped make a very scary week for my family so much better and I have my dog back now thanks to them.< /text>

Today my 7 year old Chihuahua mix, Stitch, was vomiting and off his food for two days. He definitely was not getting better as the vomiting had increased today.  My regular vet was not available and is closed tomorrow.

I had given him a jerky treat which apparently upset his digestive system.  I am so glad we found Access Speciality Animal Hospital. My little guy was feeling so bad before he went to the hospital. Dr. Luce ran tests and determined he may be having a bout of pancreatitis.  She gave him IV fluids, a long acting antibiotic shot, medicine for nausea and pain medication.  He also did an ultra sound exam of his stomach.  She sent him home with medication for nausea, and special food and a diet for a few days.  He came home clearly feeling better.  He is kind of out of it from the medications, but at least he is not suffering.  The bill was very reasonable considering this is Sunday and the treatment he received.  I want to thank Dr Luce and the staff at Access.  We will definitely go back to Access if he is not better.  We are so lucky to have this facility in the South Bay Area. < Review>
I took my pup to this clinic and I have to say that they are the best.  It's true that they are not open during regular business hours but it's great that they are open during "odd" hours. I would bullet point this but here's the breakdown of why I gave this clinic an excellent rating:

First, they are conveniently located for me.  It was about a 15 minute drive from where I live.

Second, when I called them and gave them the details of what was going on with my pup, she was having a seizure from the phone diagnosis, they told me to bring her in.

Third, the staff there is super friendly and they were very nice to my pup and me.  They checked her out and noticed I wasn't mistreating her in anyway and didn't make any presumptions of the sorts.

Fourth, they gave me a choice to have blood work done there or wait till I took her to her primary vet.  The price wasn't so bad considering they had the means to to do blood work on site.

Fifth, we were in and out of there within 1 hour.  Of course, we were the only ones there but I have to say, I was thankful for them because it was my pups first episode and in all the years I've had pets, I've never seen an animal have a seizure.

Sixth, they gave me recommendations and also what I need to do to try and keep my pup safe and healthy.

So, overall, my experience with this clinic was great and they didn't push anything on me.  They made sure I was in control of the decision making process and in no degraded me in my care of my pup.  I will go to them again if I have any more issues with my animals if it is during "odd" hours and I am not able to see my primary vet.<//Review>

This is a long review. TLDR: Horrible communication by staff members and lazy treatment of animals staying overnight.

I brought our dog in as an emergency in May 2019 because he was having a prolonged seizure and Access Animal Hospital was the closest emergency vet available. Our dog has Idiopathic epilepsy (occasional seizures due to genetic defect) and has been on various medications/diets to control them. Obviously we were stressed and expressed our frustration to the Doctor at how our dog has tried multiple medications that seem to not be working and the Doctor's response was we "have the option to put him down if it is too much for us to handle". Wish I took this as a sign to leave as I found out later that it really sums up their mentality towards treating the patients there.

Fast-forward, they suggest to keep him overnight due to the severity of the seizure to which we agree. He stays a total of 2 nights 3 days. We are allowed to visit at anytime, which we did several times. Every time we visited he was completely drugged with sleeping medication. He would be awake but in an extreme daze. We thought it was just the seizure medication at first but we realized they just tranquilize the animals during their entire stay (we expressed this concern to the doctor and it was confirmed).

Finally, we received a call Sunday morning that our dog would be ready for pickup at 1:00pm that day. I arrived at 1:00pm for pick up and was checked in. After about 15 minutes everyone in the front waiting lobby was informed that their current doctor on staff was new and therefore it would take a bit longer for everyone to be helped. I waited for 2 hours and was finally approached by a technician. The technician said our dog still had an IV line in him and they were waiting for the doctor to get to him to take it out. When asked, she wasn't sure how long that would take. I left to grab something to eat down the street when my girlfriend received a call from the technician (whose phone was on file) received a call from the tech complaining that she came out with my dog and I was gone. Saying she told me she "would be right out and that I was told it would just be a few minutes." Except, by this time we were already done eating so it was a good half an hour after I had left. We get back to Access in a few minutes and were given our dog. Going over the meds, we point out to the tech that she forgot our new medication for his seizures. We waited another 40 minutes for them to get the medication out to us. Finally we were able to go home after over 3 hours of miscommunication and frustration.

This wasn't just one incident. It wasn't just one person. This was an ordeal that spanned multiple days over multiple workers. If this was able to happen to me, someone that is actually able to remind staff that I am still there and able to voice my concern, imagine how your pets, which are not able to remind staff or able to easily express pain and frustration, are treated. P.S. this is a private vet so we paid huge amount for all of this as well.

To give credit, the woman at the front desk was extremely nice, polite and understanding. She saw my frustration and continually checked up on the techs and doctor for me. You know who you are and I greatly appreciate your empathy. Also, the neurologist, who unfortunately is only there part time, was very knowledgeable and helpful.</Review>

<text>We have spent the past 14+ years protecting our animals from a veterinary industry fueled by profit, greed and arrogant individuals. During my visit to this "Specialty" animal hospital for a consultation my experience & common sense leads me to believe the life of our beloved animal was taken by a person(s) with questionable credentials
(search 50 Things Your Vet) poor judgement & worse decision making skills. In an industry where treatment plans & succinct,  communication are common practice and key to survival there was no visible protocol. From the moment I first met someone who did not intro themselves by name, title, or area of specialty the pressure to authorize, costly, life threatening treatment never stopped. We were informed of our options and chose surgery in the hope that Pickles would regain her mobility. DR. Krebs was contacted at 2:00a.m., and performed the surgery at 4:00a.m.
We were contacted by Dr. Krebs at 8:00 a.m. to inform us that the surgery went well. It has been 3 weeks since the surgery and Pickles is doing very well. She is basically walking unassisted.

From the time we entered ACCESS to our last follow up appt., my girlfriend and I have been so impressed with the facility, staff and the wonderful skill of Dr Krebs. The care and compassion shown to Pickles by Bonnie,  and all staff members was extremely comforting to us. DR. Krebs' professionalism was very much appreciated and extremely impressive. No pet owner ever wants to see their pet in a life or death situation; however, it is comforting to know that such competent and caring individuals are available at ACCESS to assist pet owners in the South Bay.
Thank you,
Lance and Jennifer</Review><UserId.>102775336265281813299<//UserId.><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< Rate>

<user>102775336265281813299</user><username>Lance Nielsen</username>< time>
1525639486776< /time>
<rate>5< /rate>< text>
On the 16th of April, my girlfriend and I experienced what every pet owner fears, a health emergency to our 6 yr old Frenchie (Pickles). We took her to our local vet who diagnosed her with a respiratory infection and told us to monitor her. As the night progressed, we continued to watch her deterioration. By 11:00 p.m., she was unable to walk due to paralysis in her rear legs. We rushed her to ACCESS based on reviews my girlfriend had researched.  Pickles was immediately evaluated and diagnosed with a spinal cord injury ( 2 ruptured  discs).

We were informed of our options and chose surgery in the hope that Pickles would regain her mobility. DR. Krebs was contacted at 2:00a.m., and performed the surgery at 4:00a.m.
We were contacted by Dr. Krebs at 8:00 a.m. to inform us that the surgery went well. It has been 3 weeks since the surgery and Pickles is doing very well. She is basically walking unassisted.

From the time we entered ACCESS to our last follow up appt., my girlfriend and I have been so impressed with the facility, staff and the wonderful skill of Dr Krebs. The care and compassion shown to Pickles by Bonnie,  and all staff members was extremely comforting to us. DR. Krebs' professionalism was very much appreciated and extremely impressive. No pet owner ever wants to see their pet in a life or death situation; however, it is comforting to know that such competent and caring individuals are available at ACCESS to assist pet owners in the South Bay.
Thank you,
Lance and Jennifer</text>

<Gmap_id>0x80db43e151343609:0x424442d8bbb3e5d4</Gmap_id>< text>
My sister in law was traveling through town when her lower radiator hose split and caused the car to over heat. 3 weeks before she had her head gaskets and radiator replaced with new coolant, so the cooling system was clean and free of debris when it over heated. she had it towed to Certified Tire and Service for diagnosis and was told it needed a new temp sensor, 2 hoses and a cooling system flush.

I am a Ford Triple Senior Master Technician with 28 years experience but I live in Washington State and could not help. I called the shop and asked why they would need to do a flush when it was clean and Dave told me they flush cooling systems any time there was a cooling problem and told me I would have done the same thing. This is not true and not standard to the industry. Coolant flush is for cleaning dirty cooling systems, fixing electrolysis and if the coolant is old.

The shop is over selling on the repair, I asked to have the price($102+ tax) of the flush be removed and He said he couldn't do that because it was already authorized. (it was only authorized because they are over selling to a Lady with 2 young kids stuck in a town they were driving through).  The price for a broken lower rad hose, upper hose, temp sensor, and flush was $500.

My sister in law didn't have the money for the repair so I said I would pay for it. I tried to pay with my credit card but was told we couldn't unless we were there in person to sign for it. (I live in Washington State)

So now the car is fixed (unhappy about the price) but they are unwilling to take payment over the phone.

RO # 1123214 repair date 6/23/13

Mitchel labor time
Temp sensor .9hr
Upper and lower hose 1.5hr<//text>

<Rating>4</Rating><text>I visited this park with my daughter over the course of 2 weeks while visiting family in the area.
The first half of my visit the huge grass field area was unmowed and littered with dog poop from disrespectful dog owners (the park provides poo bags!) There was even an instance where my child as well as another got poop on them from the playground area, a dog had let loose near the steps of the structure.

That being said, I give this park a 4 star rating because it's generally a nice place to bring kids, that features 2 large play areas (1 big kid, 1 little kid). It's also evident to me that whoever is in charge of taking care of the park, is doing their best. Today, when we arrived at the park, one of the 2 baby swings was missing. It had been there the day before. A worker was there, taking pictures and figuring out details. He replaced the swing right then and there, which is impressive.
I will definitely bring my daughter back when we visit again. There's plenty of room to run, places to play, benches to sit and tables to eat!<//text>< Pics>

<rating>4< /rating><user>101582538573617341606< /user><pictures>None< /pictures><resp>None</resp>< review>
Great park for the whole family... BUT!
So the park is great to play with your kids or work out, or even fly a drone. There is a place for smaller kids and for those who are more grown up. There is a football field to use for private or school activities.
All good so far. Here comes the but.

After the sun sets, more adult crowd start coming out. There is lots of smoking sometimes, often weed, and unfortunately they don't wait for kids to go home. There's lots of cigarette butts later on to be found in kids playing area. And no security. So bear that in mind.<//review>

116615379659368760758<//UserId.>
<Name>D Hndz< /Name>< date>
1525648617808< /date>
< Rate>
2</Rate>
< Review>
Ambiance :

Music was painfully loud and Im used to loud . They had a mariachi which I love but their speakers were blasting  to try to cover the music from their small bar in the next room. The bar was louder than any night club and it was just a very uncomfortable experience.  I walked out with a headache.

Food:

Mediocre .  They serves in big plates that are mainly 95% rice and beans.  The food is nothing  special and overpriced.  We had Shirmp al mojo de ajo and  it was undercooked and they used garlic seasoning instead of real garlic (8 small shrimps. I counted them). We ordered salad instead of rice and beans and don't have a single homemade dressing. The spicy  salsa was basically canned chipotle  chillies with some seasoning.  The bacon wrapped shrimp was okay... bacon was a little burned . The taquitos were okay and enchilada was just okay. Margaritas tasted like a lemonade kool-aid.

This place has so much potential the place it's really nice and  they have good menu but they lack  good chef and good management.<//Review>

Our first visit EVER... Made reservations for a party of 30 a month in advance and everything was great. We were seated immediately upon arriving, chips and salsa to snack on, followed by prompt drinks. We requested orders placed first for the kids and that worked out great.. food didn't take long. In fact food was out for everyone quicker than I expected, despite ordering 10mins after the kids. Service was excellent, food was excellent... and since we were celebrating a baptism, we brought our own cake that they also cut and served for us without an additional cutting fee. Rafael, gracias por todo, fue un placer. Will definitely be back for a date night.<//review>
